This is the only photo I took on July 6th 2019, but she sure is a beauty! This night we ended up camped on a little beach near some public lands camping area. It was a beautiful spot but never again will I camp right next to water in July in Maine. As soon as dusk hit the mosquitos were out in a thick deafening cloud. Even with 100% deet they would find the tiny spot you missed and chew it up. Once inside our tent they couldn't bite anymore but the cuben fiber material just amplified their high pitched buzzing. Going out to pee later on in the night was one of the scarier moments of the whole hike üòÖ

Y'all the privies in Maine were wonderful. It was strange starting out so pampered by the nice kept up poop sheds. It was a clear breezy night so we set up in the little site at the end of the point and opened up the tent so the breeze came through off the water all night. Sunset at Rainbow Lake campsite in the 100 Mile Wilderness last 4th of July. Wishing I was back out in the peace and quiet of the woods in Maine with only the loons singing their song all night. No loud fireworks and boisterous parties, just a couple of just-beginning thru hikers and some chill section hikers enjoying the beautiful wilderness of this country we call home (for better or for worse).

A big shout out to all of you that had to cancel your hike this year. We were due to start a record attempt on the AT in July but had to postpone until next June. I‚Äôve started a Facebook group that you‚Äôre more than welcome to join.
APPALACHIAN TRAIL 2021 FKT ATTEMPT

On approximately June 1st 2021 Kristian will attempt to break the world record on the iconic Appalachian Trail. His chief crew will be Sharon Mullan who will be in charge of nutrition, logistics and driving to various meet points to resupply and refuel Kristian along the way. In the lead up to this attempt, we'll be selecting a small group of pacers, and crew that may be interested in joining us along the way. If you feel this could be something you‚Äôre interested in then please feel free to contact Sharon, who will get back to you ASAP. There are so many things to consider on an attempt of this magnitude, If you have experiences or information that you may like to share then please feel free to do so. All of your support is welcome. Happy to have you join us on our year of preparation...

"Day 89-91 |Appalachian Trail | Mile 1607-1693. The mountains were socked in with fog. I could hear the sound of cattle in the distance. I came upon a gate with a white blaze on it. I must follow the WHITE BLAZE. Upon entering the field I was greeted by a herd of long horn cattle. Surrounded by these huge animals, my mom and I carefully maneuvered down the Appalachian Trail.

It has been so AMAZING to have my mom around to backpack with me for a few days! Baby Milkshake, Maple, Cruise and I had just hiked a 40 mile day followed by a 30 mile day- just so we could make it to the Grayson Highlands before the big storm hit. We wanted to make sure we saw the wild PONIES!! And that we did! I saw over a dozen ponies roaming through the highlands‚ù§Ô∏è. This trail is truly full of SURPRISES!!" Via @sunneydelight -

Last year on the trail I was given the name "Flower" from a dear friend and hiking buddy "Bop-it" aka #bop_it_hikes . I didn't think it was very fitting seeing I wasn't pretty nor did I have a floral smell, more like a dying Ox. But I was loving on all the wonderful florals on the AT in Maine, so I took it. As we got further south all the green turned to brown and flowers no longer were around. As did my body, crumbling and emaciation set in. By the time we got south I was now called "Flower the Wilted". ü§£ As the florals bloom I feel myself feeling not so broken. Small steps everyday are why life is so beautiful.
Still I stop and admir all blooms even the wild weedsü§ó. Simplicity and balance are one needs.
There is a beauty in everything, you just have to be willing to look, even if its into silence and darkness.

2,200+ miles, 6 months. I can‚Äôt believe this journey has come to an end.
Like all thru hikers, we had our highs and lows. We hiked through thunderstorms and snow storms, crazy heat and bitter cold. We overcame many obstacles: like Maine trying to kill me frequently with new found allergies, injuries, and even a trip to the ER. We had to battle mental, physical, and emotional fatigue. Fortunately, for every hard time we have a bright memory to match. We made amazing new friends, we got engaged, we visited new places like NYC, Gettysburg, and Washington DC. I found out I‚Äôm a lot tougher than I thought, and even when I doubted myself I had Justin by my side to encourage me. We had a ‚Äòonce in a lifetime experience‚Äô.
We are now officially southbound thru hikers of the Appalachian Trail! .
.
My family came up to hike the last mile of the AT with us and for that I could not be more thankful.
For the last time on this journey, please visit the link in my bio to help us raise money and awareness for the @alzassociation .

We made it through the Smokies! It was cold and snowy when we passed the 2000 mile marker. 2000 miles! We slept at Derrick Knob Shelter, where there is literally an entire community of mice living. There were SO MANY! Luckily no one lost any food or gained any holes!

The hike to Fontana Dam was an absolutely gorgeous day. The leftover frost and snow in the morning glittered brilliantly in the sunlight. We were able to meet the awesome trail angel Fresh Grounds down by the Dam who treated us to grilled cheese and fresh cut french fries, and then to an egg skillet breakfast the next morning! He's awesome!

I still can't believe I have hiked over 2000 miles. I'm so not ready for this adventure to be over. I wish I could head straight over to the PCT in a few months!

Day 155 | 14.1 miles

After Hiker Thanksgiving, we took some time off to visit family in Tennessee. A snow storm moved in, so we spent an additional night.

I‚Äôm so glad we did - we watched football, made a traditional Sunday meal and shared a lot of laughter. It‚Äôs always special when my siblings and I get together, reminisce and share our childhood family traditions with the next generation.

We returned to a snow covered trail and I‚Äôll be honest, I took the Creeper Trail to Damascus. It was beautiful to meander along the river and much more manageable than the AT in the snow.

I definitely want to return to cycle this rails to trails section in the spring or fall.

One of the many gifts of this trail is that there are so many beautiful places to revisit and explore more in depth.

We‚Äôre officially done hiking for the season! Due to a lot of rain, ice, cold, and the close proximity to Christmas, we decided to end our hike at Newfound Gap in Great Smoky Mountains National Park. There are about 200 miles left to Springer Mountain that we will probably finish hiking during a warmer season. (Videos from the last couple months on trail are coming soon to our YouTube channel) #appalachiantrail #blueridgemountains #blueridgemoments #atsobo2019 #adventureappalachia #trektheat

Here we are, still stuck in Gatlinburg two days later. We thought the road would open today, but an hour before sunset and it's still closed. The weather for the next several days doesn't look good, so we're having to consider what to do if the road doesn't open back up tomorrow. Neither of us want to skip the next 50ish miles, but we are close enough to home to come back and clean it up later. It's definitely not ideal though. And figuring out how to get to Fontana Dam from Gatlinburg isn't fun. But on the positive side, we played a cheap round of putt-putt golf at the weirdest place I've been on trail and have been getting to know a fellow thru-hiker from the UK named Bullwinkle so that's pretty cool. I also managed to find a meeting to go to and pick up my 4 year chip! It was good to be back in the rooms again for a moment.
Well, guess it's time to start discussing options going forward üôÉ Hopefully the road opens early tomorrow and we can get back to finishing up the last 200 miles of this adventure!

Well, we made the climb into the Smokies. Then the weather went to sh*t. Our quilts managed to get wet overnight and there was no chance to dry them out today. I couldn't feel my hands for hours. So between the cold rain and the wind and the forecast sleet and snow tonight and below freezing temps tomorrow we made the call to get off trail and head into Gatlinburg at Newfound Gap. We made it just in time, as they closed the road around 3 and actually had to let our ride through to get us. Now we're stuck until they reopen the road, which won't be until Thursday morning at the earliest. I'm pretty excited to see Gatlinburg around Christmas and with a little snow on the ground!.....................................................................................................................................................................................................
Also today is my sobriety birthday! 4 years! Man, life sure has changed...grateful doesn't even begin to cover it ‚ù§

They say the trail always provides and I believe that‚Äôs true - Hiker Thanksgiving was a beautiful reminder of that.

We got to reunite in a beautiful place and enjoy incredible food (thanks to amazing trail angels) with people who trekked with us through some of our most challenging days.

So grateful for the people who helped us survive the Madison Spring Hut vortex, the person who sat with us while we tried to find a hitch to the hospital in Vermont, the couple that brought us some epic trail magic before I was diagnosed with Lyme, the human who brought the fun to countless Sunday‚Äôs, and the SOBROs who made 36 hours in the Priest Shelter somewhat bearable.

These people (not all pictured) kept us laughing and propelled us forward when we needed it the most.

Incredibly grateful our paths crossed when they did on the trail and that we had a chance to get together and reminisce on what a wild adventure this has been.

Day 149 | 9.8 miles

A rainy start to the day made way for one of the windiest days I‚Äôve had on trail since the White Mountains.

It was the day before Thanksgiving and Ryan hiked this section the day before, so I spent most of the day hiking alone. The wind was crushing me as I made my way across the ridge and I was anxious to reach tree cover.

As soon as I reached the tree line and began to descend, I was wishing I was back on the balds. A tree fell just a few feet from me and my adrenaline kicked in. I began sprinting down the trail. The miles seemed to crawl by even though I was making good time.

I made it to the car. The enchantment I had with the trail the day before, had completely vanished.

It‚Äôs all part of the Appalachian Trail Rollercoaster, some days you‚Äôre so deeply enamored with the beauty and adventure of it all, other days you‚Äôre anxious to make it to the road, the next shelter or town.

A year ago, we made the decision to hike the Appalachian Trail.

We loosely made plans, but knew that this trek wasn‚Äôt guaranteed. I had to make it through two scans without any major hiccups. We had to resign from our jobs, move out of our home, and find a place for our fur babe, Lucky, to thrive while we were away.

After we got the all clear from my medical team, this adventure became real. I knew I needed to take risks in my personal life in order to grow in other aspects of my life, but leaving my corporate dream job and yoga community was incredibly difficult.

The transition was filled with mixed emotions, but I found reassurance and gratitude by grounding down in the present and trusting the process. For the first time, I was taking steps to create the life I imagined rather than just showing up for it.

Over the last 5 months on the trail, nothing has gone according to plan. We‚Äôve had more obstacles and challenges than I could have possibly imagined. The one constant has been actively choosing to take on each challenge, to trust the process and find gratitude in each day.

Sometimes in the day to day, we lose sight of the big picture, of how far we‚Äôve come, of what we‚Äôve accomplished and what we are capable of. Today, I was reminded of that and so much more as I trekked through the snow in virtual solitude reflecting on the last 365 days.

Day 148 | 7.2 miles

There‚Äôs something about this section of trail that had me fully captivated.

The forest that leads to Grayson Highlands reminded me of Maine and New Hampshire.

The sound of the streams that ran through the trail took me back to a time when the trek was slow, the climbs were hard but rewarding, and my curiosity about the world around me seemed endless.

It is pretty amazing that the sounds of nature have become as powerful as music, with the ability to take me back to times and places.

Oh, and the wild ponies were pretty cool too.

Day 147 | 6.2 miles

Some days you‚Äôre up, some days you‚Äôre down.

I was moving the Jeep mid day and noticed the tire pressure was low. I didn‚Äôt have any service and knew I wouldn‚Äôt be able to fill the tire and make the miles we mapped out for the day, so I opted to go to the nearest road @_rolson would cross to problem solve.

I knew this would put Ryan ahead of me in miles and I was so discouraged by the fact we didn‚Äôt have service and weren‚Äôt able to communicate.

Thankfully, it wasn‚Äôt a serious emergency, but it definitely made me think about the inherent risks of slacking ourselves, especially with the dropping temperatures and lack of hikers out here.

It seems so simple, but some days it feels so uncertain and stressful as we adapt to our new normal on trail.

Day 146 | 19.3 miles

After taking some time off trail to wait for test results, we hit the trail with a new plan.

I fortunately got the all clear on Lyme disease, but have lost so much weight and have been feeling incredibly fatigued and weak.

We opted to experiment with slacking ourselves while I regain some strength.

Our first day, I was so nervous. It was snowing, I was worried about whether or not I‚Äôd be able to make the miles and I was worried about hiking alone.

It‚Äôs a big adjustment, but ultimately it brings us closer to completing this trail. Plus, it always feels good to conquer another 4K foot mountain and to put some miles down.

Wander and wonder ‚ú®

Before I left for the trail I made a lot of lists. I jotted down why I was hiking the AT, how I would feel if I finished it, how I would feel if I didn‚Äôt and what taking on the AT meant to me at that point in my life.

I look back on those lists often for reassurance. I also look back at them and think about how much I‚Äôve changed. I was fueled by ego in some ways, I was afraid of failure in other ways, but at my core, I wanted to discover pieces of myself I‚Äôd lost. I wanted to rebuild. I wanted to have the courage and confidence to create my life, rather than show up and respond to it.

Over the last few weeks, in the quest for miles on the AT, I lost the awe. I lost sight of the beauty that this trail holds.

Today, I found it again. I fell so deeply in love with the Appalachian Trail for the 1,000th time. I fell so in love I barely hiked more than 8 miles. I cried because I didn‚Äôt meet my mileage goal for the day. Then I watched the sunset while I ate dinner and cried some more, because I realized maybe it‚Äôs not about the miles walked - maybe it‚Äôs about never losing sight of wandering and wondering.

Day 139 | 24.1 miles

We were on the trail before the sun, trekking down together from Chestnut Knob Shelter.

We moved through some fields and took in the night sky. As the sun came up we began to break up and settled into our individual paces. I still wasn‚Äôt feeling well, so Goat took on a lot of my pack weight to make it easier for me to hike out. We were all running out of food, but we all shared what we had to boost morale and energy levels.

Speed Queen got a bit turned around in a field, so we ended up reuniting to make the final push into town.

The last few miles felt a bit easier than the miles we had behind us - we were once again trekking together by headlamp, energized to get to town and eat.

Secretly, we all thought it may be our last Sunday Funday together, so we were determined to make it a good one.

Fortunately, we are hoping to catch up to üèéüëë, so the Sunday Funday‚Äôs can continue all the way to GA.

We've been busy since getting back on trail! We made it past 1700 miles and the 3/4 way mark. We have less than 500 miles to go! Actually less than 450 as I'm writing this. We're night hiking pretty much every evening now, there's really no other way to get the miles in. The coldest part of most days is right before dawn, so getting up earlier is just so hard to do. So walking into the night it is.
We finally made it to Grayson Highlands and we couldn't have asked for a more perfect day. The infamous wild ponies were adorable. It was so hard to contain my excitement over them! It's awesome to still be able to have new experiences so far into this trail.
I'm definitely excited to finish this adventure but I really don't know how I'm going to adjust to "regular" life again. Well, that's a problem for another day!

Day 133 | 19.3 miles

After a pretty wild 26.2 mile day, we slack packed another 19.3.

We were all sore and tired, but @rdwagoner picked us up first thing and took us to the most incredible gas station. We devoured breakfast biscuits and home made donuts, exactly what we needed to jumpstart our day.

The first few miles were fairly easy but the terrain got more challenging towards the end of the day. We weren‚Äôt going to make our slack meet up time and we had no service.

@_rolson still had some energy, so he sprinted the final few miles by headlamp to meet up with our trail angel while @pattiehikes and I made our way down.

The time it took to descend felt like an eternity, so we killed time by talking about life while simultaneously hoping the road wasn‚Äôt too far.

We emerged at the road to find the guys waiting for us with amazing food and beers.

Successfully crushed 45.5 miles in 2 days!

I‚Äôve been in survival mode the last 7-10 days. I didn‚Äôt even realize it until someone asked me how I am doing out here.

I‚Äôve been waking up to hike before the sun rises and getting into camp long after it sets. I‚Äôm exhausted, but I‚Äôve come too far and given up way too much to quit now.

I‚Äôm still enjoying each day, thanks in large part to the amazing community of SOBOs out here - who I can simultaneously commiserate and laugh with.

I feel connected to this adventure but so detached from my life off trail. I‚Äôm struggling to find a balance.

I miss my family, my friends, my pup. I miss the idea of home, but know that there isn‚Äôt a place of my own to go back to.

I know the real work will begin once this trek is over, which makes the time out here that much more special.

I know I‚Äôll miss this trail. I know I‚Äôll miss the simplicity of this life. As the days have gotten colder and I‚Äôm rushing to crunch out miles, I am trying not to lose sight of how beautiful and transformative this experience has been. I‚Äôm trying not to wish away the remaining days and miles - and all of the lessons they will undoubtedly hold. I‚Äôm trying not to lose sight of how lucky I am to be out here, 1,200 miles into an adventure I once dreamed of but never thought possible.

Like the trail, it‚Äôs easier said than done some days, but that‚Äôs what makes each day out here so meaningful.

Day 132 | 26.2 miles

Our first marathon day on trail began with a pretty legit climb up Dragon‚Äôs Tooth. The ascent reminded me of New England and it was kind of fun to be back in more rugged terrain (although it was less than an ideal start to what would be a long day). We completed the last piece of the Virginia Triple Crown and enjoyed spectacular views before crossing the Eastern Continental Divide and making our way to camp via headlamp.

It was an incredibly exhausting marathon day, but it was totally worth it because we raised over $1,000 for cancer research, hit the halfway point (1,096 miles hiked), crossed the 1,100 mile mark and are that much closer to finishing this wild adventure.

Day 125 | 20.1 miles

This trek is really hard some days. It‚Äôs also really beautiful. 9 times out of 10, I look back on the hard moments with some level of gratitude.

The reality is, the epic and beautiful moments wouldn‚Äôt be so bright if it weren‚Äôt for the breakdowns, the setbacks and the challenges.

We hiked down the ridge with the sun, pausing to take it all in, even though it meant we‚Äôd finish the day by headlamp.

These are the moments that put it all into perspective.

Day 123 | 0 miles
Day 124 | 20.6 miles

Never have I ever hiked through a tropical storm, hunkered down in a shelter for 36 hours and woken up to my gear frozen.

Oh wait, I‚Äôve done all of the above and hiked in my crocs for 6 miles because my trail runners were frozen solid.

Our gear didn‚Äôt dry out while we were sheltering through the storm, the temp dropped well below freezing and my normal hiking clothes were frozen solid (see pic 2 for how rigid my shirt, hat and shoes were). At first, no one else was awake and I shed a few silent tears. It was the first moment for me on this trek where I really questioned why I was out here. I was cold, my gear was frozen, and we were 20 miles from the closest town. I was miserable.

The conditions are only going to get worse and there was once a time I thought I‚Äôd finish this trek by Thanksgiving and now we are looking at mid Jan due to all the setbacks. I definitely had a mini pity party in the darkness as I packed up my things.

As others began to wake up and face the frozen reality of that morning, the tears quickly turned to laughter.

The trek must go on and while the terrain has been amazing, the elements are testing us in new and strenuous ways by pushing our mental limits.

Day 122 | 15.3 miles

Our first 4,000 foot mountain since New Hampshire!

The Priest definitely chastised us the entire way up - we walked through a complete downpour. Fortunately, the climb up was pretty warm.

Unfortunately, the temp dropped quickly and the last mile to the shelter was brutally cold.

We made it to the shelter and quickly changed into dry clothes.

We ended up getting stuck at the Priest Shelter for over 36 hours with 5 other people as the rain, intense winds and eventual cold front moved through.

We kept ourselves entertained by reading the confessions in the log book and sharing stories from the trail.

We finished backpacking the Smokies today. The experience leaves me speechless. .
We started on Tuesday with blue skies and inviting weather. Wednesday is when that weather turned - cooler temps and hazy rain. Thursday called for our first on trail zero; we agreed this was the safest option for us as opposed to hiking in intense rain and dropping temperatures. Friday morning left us hiking in the snow with such incredible views. All this way we have been hiking upon mountain ridge tops on narrow trails, views on either side. Saturday gave us opportunity to meet new friends and savor the last of the views. Today, we sleep cozily in lodge beds and look forward to effortless hot coffee tomorrow morning.
I just really can‚Äôt put into words how grateful I am for this experience and how much pure bliss I felt in each and every step, even if I couldn‚Äôt feel my toes. .

Spoiler Alert: today we will hit 1,000 miles on the Appalachian Trail.

While this feels like a big milestone, the 1,192 miles left ahead of us, as the nights and days are getting colder, have me feeling a bit defeated.

So to help me turn this into more of a celebration instead of the, ‚Äúoh my dang, we still have so far to walk‚Äù moment that it is - I‚Äôm asking y‚Äôall to help me raise $1,000 ($1 for every mile on this trail I‚Äôve walked) for innovative cancer research at Dana-Farber Cancer Institute.

I feel incredibly grateful for Dana-Farber and the amazing care I‚Äôve received there over the last 10 years. Paying it forward to this organization by running the Boston Marathon has given me a new sense of self and made me believe anything is possible (including hiking the AT, which at the moment I feel like is a big reach). When I started raising money for DFMC 4 years ago, I wasn‚Äôt sure what scared me more, raising $10k or running 26.2 miles. Y‚Äôall showed up big time for me year after year and I hope you‚Äôll help me reach my goal this year of $15,000.

Today we waited out the storms in a motel in Buchanan, VA. It's nice having an unplanned rest day, but it does slow down our pace. I have no illusions that we will somehow avoid encountering winter weather but I just hope we can finish before it's too bad. It's funny, I started this hike with this purist mentality of hitting every white blaze, in order, from Katahdin to Springer Mountain. Now that we've been on trail for over 1400 miles, I realize that there's so much more to this trail than just hitting milestones and making miles. It's fun to push my body and mind past it's limits, but it's also fun to relax at an awe-inspiring overlook or spend time hanging out with a friend and his cool-ass dog. If we have to trudge through snow and ice, we'll trudge until it becomes unsafe. And if it becomes unsafe, we can come back later. The trail will be here waiting. For now, I'm just ready to get back on trail and see what Southern VA has to offer. I hear it's amazing üòä

So we actually finished the Shenandoah National Park section over a week ago, and it is one of my favorite parts so far! The terrain is mostly smooth under my feet, the climbs and descents are gradual and filled with switchbacks. This is what my naive mind thought the whole trail would be like üòÖ. I've been waiting for the fall colors and they have been popping lately! I finally got my first 30+ mile day in SNP (34!) and it was honestly so invigorating! We hiked late into the night and ended up treeing a couple cubs. Luckily Mama Bear never popped up. I love Virginia!

Oh also Chris solidified his future as a cobbler by once again frankenstitching his failing shoes. 5 years and I'm still surprised at how resourceful he can be üòç

Day 116 | 11.6 miles

Virginia, I‚Äôve missed you. Shenandoah, I‚Äôve missed you more.

After two zeros, we arrived in Shenandoah.

Whenever I take time off trail, I always feel a bit anxious as I near the trailhead. Sometimes it‚Äôs because I barely touched my long to do list, other times it‚Äôs because I‚Äôm not ready to unplug again, to disconnect from the world that can so quickly and easily distract me from my thoughts and the solitude of trail life.

Arriving in Shenandoah, I was instantly at ease.

Shenandoah is the place I came to when I needed to rebuild my strength post cancer, it‚Äôs the place that has always been there to help me navigate grief, and it‚Äôs the place where I‚Äôve walked through darkness, but always found light. Shenandoah is the place that taught me sorrow and joy live side by side, and gratitude is essential to finding balance.

It‚Äôs the place that reminds me the sun will always rise and there is always another mountain to climb or waterfall to explore before the sun inevitably sets on another day.

It‚Äôs the place that has always been my escape from the world, and it‚Äôs the place that helped me learn to navigate the ridges and valleys of this one beautiful life I‚Äôve been given.

For the first time on the AT, I truly feel at home. In so many ways, it feels right that I will ultimately end my 2,192 mile journey here.

Day 113 | 7.1 miles

We woke up early and hiked to the Secret Shelter. We planned on hiking another 7 miles, but couldn‚Äôt turn down trail magic that got us into NYC at 3 pm instead of midnight.

We arrived in NYC, went to Shake Shack and trekked over to Times Square.

In so many ways, I used to fit into this city. I‚Äôd come into town for work, be perpetually busy, never look up from my phone or make eye contact with strangers. I felt empowered, but under the facade, I lacked a lot of confidence.

No doubt, I stood out like a sore thumb when we got to NYC. Before this trek, I would‚Äôve felt so self conscious - no make up, haven‚Äôt showered in days, and I am far from fashionable. I was surprised that I didn‚Äôt care.

There have been so many points on this trek where I‚Äôve reflected about how much has changed. This moment hit me unexpectedly, in the best possible way.

Day 112 | 19.5 miles

We crossed into our 7th and final state before making our jump down to Virginia.

New Jersey welcomed us with the Stairway to Heaven (for NOBOs), which was more of a hellish descent in the rain for us as SOBOs.

Luckily, there was coffee and apple cider donuts at a farm nearby. We warmed up, before enjoying some of the legendary New Jersey boardwalks. We even stumbled past a wedding.

After an eventful and rain filled day, we made it to the shelter, where there was some trail magic - beer in the bear box.

Day 111 | 15.8 miles

My relationship with the AT changes daily. Some days I‚Äôm on cloud 9, other days are rocky at best.

I definitely wasn‚Äôt feeling this rocky day. Our pace slowed and I found myself relying more on upper body strength to navigate the terrain. The blazes were as difficult to spot as I am in this photo and we definitely lost the trail more than once.

We made it to the road and I wanted nothing more than to call it a day. The idea of going 2.6 more miles through rocky terrain was not appetizing. Ryan helped me to rally, but I wasn‚Äôt totally amped about it.

Turned out the final 2.6 miles consisted of a lovely footpath along a ridge.

It‚Äôs easy to let the terrain that‚Äôs behind us influence how we approach the terrain ahead. It‚Äôs hard to push through the uncertainty and anxiety of what‚Äôs ahead, especially after a long day. It‚Äôs rewarding when you get to your campsite and realize it wasn‚Äôt as bad as you thought it would be. It‚Äôs all relative.

Okay folks I‚Äôve been feelin a whole lot of emotions lately. I finished Massachusetts, Connecticut, New York, and most of New Jersey. But most importantly, when I went through ny I finally got to hike through my home state and my home town. I got to relive a lot of good shit like my first real hike up cat rock and my first backpacking trip up west mountain. 84 rock, bear mountain, the pawling boardwalk, Warwick drive in, bulls bridge, nuclear lake, etc. didn‚Äôt realize how much of my life has already been spent on the AT. Felt better than I imagined when I started to recognize places I‚Äôve been going my whole life after hiking for so long.
Took a couple days at home to see my people and my animals and feel like a normal human again and it was amazing. Gets harder to leave every time, especially now that the weathers getting colder and people seem to be quitting left and right, but here I go lol 859.4 down, 1332.6 left

Day 110| 18.6 miles

We took a zero in Peakskill to resupply and get out of the rain. It was our first zero since we got back on trail and it was much needed.

We hit the trail early the next morning and walked across the bridge as the sun began to rise. We went over Bear Mountain and traversed the ridge line which produced some beautiful views of the New York City Skyline.

We ended the day at one of the most stunning stealth sites by Island Pond and ate dinner as the sun went down.

Day 107 | 15.9 miles

It‚Äôs been awhile since we hiked into the golden hour, especially as the days have gotten shorter.

I won‚Äôt lie, I prefer to hike by headlamp in the morning rather than in the evening. There‚Äôs something about knowing the sun will be coming up soon that is more comforting.

After a fairly uneventful day, we found ourselves reaching the golden hour and rather than rush to camp, I savored it. There was no real view to be had, but the way the light changed through the trees was pretty spectacular.

Missing water sources like this, but grateful for @guthookguides and the comments with up to date information on water flow, trail angels who provide jugs of water in containers on their property, and for deli‚Äôs that let us camp behind them so we can camel up on water to start the day (also grateful for hot coffee from said deli, because let‚Äôs be real, I‚Äôm not getting my stove going in the AM for hot coffee). New York‚Äôs streams are dry, the wells at shelters are dry or contaminated, so we are limited to pond water or beaver dams which can be less than ideal.

I know the further south we go, the longer our water carries will be, but I‚Äôm grateful for the random acts of kindness and hospitality shown here in New York.

I definitely took stream reliability for granted and am overwhelmed by the way this community shows up to support hikers.

We decided to take a little break from backpacking to tandem bike through Pennsylvania and Maryland. We will start backpacking again once we reach Harper‚Äôs Ferry, WV (peep our thru-hiker tag in the back). This decision was partly to catch up on some miles but mostly because it‚Äôs a lot of fun. As someone who has very little cycling experience, I‚Äôve learned a couple of things while cycling through PA this week: 1) Cycling in the rain is not fun, but cycling through the rain in heavy wind is even less fun. 2) Lubing the bike is super important, and if the brake is not properly lubed it might stop working while you are speeding down a hill into traffic. 3) Trying to ride a tandem bike up a mountain with no gears is pretty much impossible, but you will get an excellent upper body workout while you push it to the top. I also wanted to give a huge thank you to Ben and Katie, who graciously took us into their home two nights ago and introduced us to the long-distance hiking community Warm Showers. Overall, the past week has been a lot of fun but also a lot more work than I expected. It‚Äôs also nice that @magnuslihn does such a good job steering and navigating (neither of which I can do sitting in the back), and I‚Äôm pretty sure he can fix basically any mechanical problem that might happen with the bike. #atsobo2019 #thruhike #trektheat #tandembike #warmshowers

Day 106 | 20.5 miles

First official 20 mile day on the AT! We‚Äôve had over 20 mile days, but these 20.5 miles were all Appalachian Trail miles.

We crunched out 8 miles before 11 am and met up with @jane_haslam_photography for a quick photo shoot. She partners with @justin_goodhart_photography to take photos of AT thru hikers. The joint project is shared on @harlemvalleyathp and is absolutely amazing!

We enjoyed connecting with Jane, reflecting on why we chose the AT, reminiscing on what we‚Äôve learned thus far and musing about our ambitions post trail.

To be in this spot feels pretty special and we are so grateful for Jane and Justin - the way the capture thru hikers is genuine and authentic (and somehow they make us look good even when we haven‚Äôt showered for days). We get the photos in a few weeks and can‚Äôt wait to share them.

It was a picture perfect day of some truly spectacular and relatively gentle terrain.

Welcome to New York!

I won‚Äôt lie, leaving New England, I‚Äôm having all the feels - grateful for all that we experienced, sad to be leaving the familiar places and wild spaces that formed my love of the mountains as a child, and excited for all that is ahead.

Day 101 | 19.7 miles

The weather is starting to clear and we are increasing our mileage even more.

The terrain is a little bit of everything - meandering around ponds, wondering along farms and a bit of hand over hand climbing to reach mountain tops.

I had this theory that the southern part of each state is more challenging than the rest of the state, but I‚Äôve decided it‚Äôs all relative.

Just when I think I have a state figured out or I‚Äôve gained confidence in my mastery of the terrain, it gets switched up, and I‚Äôm humbled yet again.

I‚Äôve loved exploring the AT in my home state of Massachusetts. Excited to see what Connecticut has in store for us tomorrow.

Day 100 | 16 miles

It‚Äôs been 100 days since we summited Katahdin. We‚Äôve hiked over 650 miles, through 4 states, and I can‚Äôt begin to count the number of mountains we‚Äôve climbed (both literal and figurative). The last 100 days weren‚Äôt exactly what I envisioned, given over a quarter of them were spent off trail due to various setbacks.

With each setback, I‚Äôve learned so much. It‚Äôs what makes this adventure truly worthwhile. Prior to the trail, I was involved in countless things from my day job, to teaching yoga, to volunteering, to fundraising - it was easy to offset a setback in one arena with success in another.

Out here, I have one singular goal. The uncertainty of this adventure weighs on us in compounding ways, but I also have to recognize life is uncertain. Would it be easy to go back to our life pre-trail and latch on to what felt comfortable and secure? Yes, most days it in fact would. The reality is, we create our own sense of security and comfort. Pre-trail, I was perpetually busy, avoiding conflict and difficult decisions. Out here, I think all day long while I walk, have to face challenges head on and am forced to make decisions.

This adventure has opened me up in ways I couldn‚Äôt fathom and I am so grateful for every misstep, setback and obstacle we‚Äôve overcome.

The days are long, but so full. There is rarely a bad day on trail, because there is always a little light. Sometimes we don‚Äôt always see it, but it‚Äôs there, even if it‚Äôs in hindsight.

I‚Äôm learning to laugh at myself more, to let go of the daily frustrations and to accept all that this trail is and all that it is helping me to discover about myself and become.

Thank you for being a part of this wild adventure and for all the support y‚Äôall have showed me over the last 100 days and beyond.

P.S. Shoutout to Mother Nature for a stunning and colorful 100th day on trail.

Day 99 | 8.8 miles

We hiked by headlamp, until the sun came up. We were determined to get miles in ahead of the rain.

Unfortunately, the rain caught us. Fortunately, we weren‚Äôt far from Upper Goose Pond Cabin.

Formerly a private escape, the cabin is now owned by the National Park Service and maintained by volunteers who whip up coffee and pancakes each morning for AT thru hikers and section hikers. The cabin has no electricity or running water, but it‚Äôs cozy and full of character.

We arrived soaking wet. I quickly changed and pulled out my journal and kindle. The volunteer caretaker and her pup were a true delight as were the other thru hikers who welcomed a respite from the inch and a half of rain we got.

We built a fire in the fireplace and enjoyed the sound of the rain falling on the roof.

My only regret is not capturing a photo of this beautiful place, but here are the few photos I did snap.

Day 98 | 5 miles

After a picture perfect day and an incredible stay with Mountain Air, we got back on trail.

It started misting and raining as soon as we started making moves.

It seems we‚Äôve had more rainy days since we‚Äôve been back than sunny ones, but the streams that had gone dry are starting to flow again, so I‚Äôm grateful for the rain. It‚Äôs shortening our water carries significantly, which is giving me time to regain my strength without overdoing it.

There‚Äôs always a silver lining to less than ideal days, and having reliable water sources is definitely today‚Äôs.

Day 97 | 18.9 miles

Our longest mileage day on trail was overflowing with so. much. dang. love.

After the coldest night and our first frost, we hit the trail early. We came over Mt Williams and approached a familiar trail junction/ski trail - we were headed up Greylock for the second time in our lives. This time, as thru hikers.

Reaching Bascom Lodge was borderline emotional for me. I remember being here a few summers back, thinking about how incredible it must feel to reach this beautiful place (with amazing food) by foot. I wondered what was going through thru hikers minds and how they felt about themselves as they progressed towards Maine from Georgia. (I know, going SOBO didn‚Äôt cross my mind back then). To be here as a thru hiker, leaves me speechless in the best possible way.

We met a dear First Descents/Genentech friend with her crew at the summit and hiked 9 miles with them before parting ways and getting to catch up with Diva for a bit. We met Diva near Lyme, NH and she is one amazing human.

We made it to the trailhead and enjoyed an amazing dinner and shower followed by a warm bed thanks to Mountain Air! My heart is overflowing with gratitude for these beautiful humans who are such a special part of this journey.

Of the three of us who hiked the Appalachian Trail, Fizzy & Bear were the only ones who never questioned their ability to complete it. No matter what crazy distance goals they set themselves, or what the trail threw at them, they never once said enough. When they announced their intention to complete the final thousand miles in 36 days I was sure it was more that they were capable of. It wasn‚Äôt. Yet there were days when I would have happily thrown in the towel. Over the endless climbs and weeks of rain, as the trail chipped away at me, it only made them stronger.

Looking back now, what I learned most from 2,000 miles with F&B, was never to assume that my limitations define their limitations (thankfully they don‚Äôt). Recently this lesson has seemed all the more apposite, because whether its kids who hike, or kids who strike for our climate, it‚Äôs clear they can aspire to, and achieve more than many are willing to give them credit for. Our best hope is that they can accomplish what this generation lacks the courage to.

Underestimate them at your peril... .

Day 95 | 12.4 miles

Making my way down the trail, hiking fast, trees pass and I‚Äôm home bound üéµ

600 miles on trail AND we walked into my home state of Massachusetts.

Saying goodbye to Vermont was bittersweet.

Each state challenges me in new and different ways. Vermont terrain was pure perfection, but my thru hike came close to an abrupt end when I was unable to put down miles on the most wonderful footpath I‚Äôve seen yet.

After being diagnosed with Lyme Disease, I wasn‚Äôt sure if I‚Äôd finish the Vermont section, let alone the AT.

Coming back to the trail, I was definitely nervous and anxious, but I had my sights set on MA.

To walk up to the state line was pretty surreal and to hit 600 miles on trail the same day made for pure magic.

Day 93 | 11.5 miles

After some incredible weather, the wind, rain and fog finally caught up to us.

Within the first two hours of hiking, I slipped and went ankle deep into muddy water. Typically there are several expletives I‚Äôd blurt out on such an occasion, but I was barely phased. In fact, I laughed a bit.

I‚Äôm noticing more and more that I‚Äôve stopped fighting the AT. I‚Äôve given up on creating the perfect plan and have just learned to let go and be in this experience.

Later, I walked head first into a fallen down tree while trying to avoid mud and knocked myself backwards into the mud. There were tears (and I developed a solid egg on my head). That‚Äôs the Appalachian Trail Rollercoaster for ya.

Sometimes you take the high trail and laugh it off, other times you cry in a mud pit, but mostly you experience so much in a day that you can‚Äôt help but be grateful when you crawl into your sleeping bag at night after another eventful day.

Day 91 | 2.8 miles

We had a busy day in town before heading back on trail.

As we prepared to hitch out of town, we met a rad Long Trail thru hiker and the three of us were able to score a hitch out of town. We chatted at the trailhead for quite some time before parting ways.

I was feeling pretty run down, so we opted to do 2.8 miles to the closest shelter where we met some more thru hikers.

After a few days of tenting and sheltering by ourselves, it was nice to see other people and exchange stories about our experiences thus far. It‚Äôs definitely been more isolating since we came back to the trail, which is nice at times but can quickly become lonely.

I snapped this pic as we made our way to the shelter, the fall foliage still has me in awe.

Day 88 | 9.8 miles

Fall has arrived and it‚Äôs transformed the mundane moments into breathtaking ones.

As I left camp, I was already lost in thought. Meanwhile, @_rolson was snapping away. This seemingly ordinary moment wasn‚Äôt lost on him.

We trekked through some lovely terrain before descending into a gorge that reminded us of one of our favorite hikes in Shenandoah - Little Devils Stairs.

On any other day, this descent would be irritating, but today, it was alive with color and vastly different than the terrain we‚Äôve traversed thus far in Vermont.

We made it to the shelter as the rain was coming down and enjoyed a quiet afternoon of reading and journaling before we were evicted by mice.

Today reminded me how important perspective is. It also reminded me not to lose sight of the seemingly mundane moments.

Day 87 | 13.8 miles

And I will walk 500 miles and I will walk 500 more (+another 1,092) just to be the one who walks 2,192 miles to Georgiaüéµ

That‚Äôs not exactly how the song goes, but I‚Äôm digging it. Today was epic for a few reasons:

1. We crushed some mileage over Killington first day back, after being told 3 weeks ago my body may not be capable of hiking the AT.

2. We hit 500 miles on trail. Yes, it‚Äôs day 87, yes we thought this would happen on day 66, but the trail had other plans for us.

It takes a lot to come back, especially when you have to let go of what you envisioned your journey would look like.

It‚Äôs also still a gamble, there are no guarantees on the trail (or in life for that matter). We both know how quickly this journey can end due to unforeseen circumstances. In some ways it seemed easier to call it a hike, because we can‚Äôt possibly prepare for every situation that can arise on trail.

Then we remembered, the trail provides and this is exactly where we are meant to be.

Day 86 | 0 miles

After 17 days at home in Massachusetts with my parents, we are getting back on trail.

I have to shout out my parents. Not only did they drive us to Katahdin Stream Campground (üì∏ 1 - I was such a trail newbie), they have been shipping supplies to us and caring for our pup.

When I got sick, my Dad came to get us from Hanover, NH and my Mom had dinner waiting for us. I was basically silent the entire meal, but my parents and brother cracked jokes to see who could get me to laugh.

The last 17 days I was far from myself - exhausted, emotional and truly disengaged as I sorted through what was happening and what it meant. They were super patient with me and offered tidbits of advice at the right moments (when they knew I was ready to hear it). When they first dropped us on the trail, it was hard. There were a lot of emotions and doubt swirling through my mind.

Leaving this time was emotional, but we have close to 500 miles behind us and know what we are capable of.

We are nervous and excited to be back. Cheesing real hard in üì∏ 2 at White River Junction before catching our next bus to Killington.

Days 77-85: 0 miles

After 17 days off trail, I‚Äôm finally feeling strong enough to head back out.

Over the last few days as I‚Äôve come back to full strength, we‚Äôve explored local parks with our pup and I even laced up my hockey skates and enjoyed some time on the ice to celebrate my 31st birthday.

As we head into fall, I can‚Äôt help but think about how much we‚Äôve changed during this adventure. I‚Äôm looking forward to all that is ahead of us.

Given the close to 21 days I‚Äôve had to take off trail for my concussion and Lyme disease, we‚Äôve decided to hike to New Jersey then skip ahead to my second home state of Virginia.

We‚Äôd like to beat as much of winter in the Smokies as possible.

Once we make it to Georgia, we will fly back to New Jersey and close the gap.

It‚Äôs not the picture perfect ending on Springer that we envisioned, but it will enable us to finish our thru hike and we will end in Shenandoah - a place of personal significance as it‚Äôs where we began hiking after my first cancer diagnosis a decade ago.

Thank you for all the birthday wishes, anniversary wishes and well wishes. We are so grateful for all the love and support!

Day 75 | 4.4 miles
Day 76 | 3.8 miles

After some serious time off trail, I wasn‚Äôt willing to take another full week to recover. I figured taking on some easy miles would be manageable and that making some progress towards Georgia, even if it was slow, would be better than another week at home.

Before returning to the green tunnel, we had a long street walk, complete with a well marked side walk and some beautiful signs in front of the homes that line the trail.

Despite the easy terrain, I quickly realized that hiking is only part of the challenge. Everything we do on trail requires more energy - filtering water, setting up/breaking down camp, cooking food. Seemingly basic tasks were now draining the limited energy I had.

It became clear that if I want to make it to Georgia, I need to give myself time to fully recover. At full strength, I could hike this section in 2 and a half days. Yet here I was struggling to gain 50 miles over the course of 6 days.

I was pushing myself farther from my goal because the idea of sitting at home felt fruitless. I failed to realize that progress isn‚Äôt always about the miles. While it feels passive to be at home, I am working towards my ultimate goal.

Day 67 | 11.4 miles

It poured through the night and throughout the entire day.

We woke up to my crocs floating outside of our tent. It was kind of comical to have our own pond front property.

Having a river run through our tent as we started to pack up jumpstarted our day.

Despite the rain, we knew some sunshine was coming our way thanks to Borderline and Longshanks. They were ahead of us on trail, taking time off to visit with their family. We resupplied, enjoyed an awesome meal, photobombed a 70 year old‚Äôs birthday party and then hung out at our campsite.

The conversations and laughter were just what we needed after a long few days.

So grateful for the friends we‚Äôve made along the trail and the way this community shows up for one another. It really is magical.

Day 66 | 10.6 miles

A bear trolled us most of the night. Fortunately our bear hang was far from our tent, but we heard the rumbling and thrashing as it attempted to get to our food. We made noise whenever it came close to our tent.

Needless to say, I slept before the sun went down and after it came up, which meant we got a late start to the day.

We wondered through some beautiful fields and meandered through lovely wooded footpaths. We spotted a bear coming out of its den and watched it from afar.

Eventually we made our way to The Lookout, a cabin on private property that is open for hikers to use as a shelter. It‚Äôs a pretty amazing spot, a true gem on the trail.

After spending some time up there, we made our way down to a stealth site near a stream.

Day 60 | 4.6 miles

We had some beautiful weather and terrain for our 60th day on trail. The terrain meandered through fields and old wooded properties, complete with Apple trees.

Our big mileage goals were cut short because I wasn‚Äôt feeling well. I will admit, it wasn‚Äôt one of my best days on trail. I was frustrated by my inexplainable exhaustion and inability to pull big miles in such perfect terrain.

It felt like my thru hike was getting harder, when the terrain was visibly much easier.

Photos courtesy of Coach TenBears "Half Gallon Challenge
by Cumberland Valley Visitors Bureau

A play on words has never tasted so sweet! The Cumberland Valley is home to the midway point of the 2,180-mile Appalachian Trail. This famous trail includes some famous traditions. Historically when thru-hikers pass near the midway point they will stop at the Pine Grove Furnace General Store (located in Pine Grove Furnace State Park) and chow down on a half-gallon of Hershey's ice cream.

It might seem like an easy feat for a thru-hiker, some known to burn around 5,000 calories a day while hiking the famed Georgia to Maine footpath. However, the brick of ice cream can still be considered a "challenge" for most.

What do hikers walk (or hike) away with? A commemorative wooden spoon stamped with "Member of the Half Gallon Club" and the sweet smell of success.
Visitors to the Pine Grove Furnace General Store can enjoy flipping through the composition notebook filled with hiker tales of attempted and finished half-gallons. Some brag they could "still eat a cheeseburger" while others dream of "sleeping it off on the trail." While visiting Pine Grove Furnace State Park plan a stop at the Appalachian Trail Museum, the only museum in the country dedicated to hiking. This museum highlights the unique stories of the trail and the people that have traversed it. You will learn about interesting people like Grandma Gatewood who was the first solo female hiker to complete the entire trail at age 67.
This museum also features examples of A.T. shelters and thru-hiker memoirs. If you stop by on the right day you can mingle with the thru-hikers in the lounge area.

Author: Cumberland Valley Visitors Bureau"

Day 66 |Appalachian Trail | Mile 1125-1169. That‚Äôs right, I hiked the ‚Äú4 STATE CHALLENGE‚Äù!!! 44 miles within 24hours. We woke up at 1:30am, strapped our headlamps on and broke down camp as quick as we could. My friend Mountain Calf (a NOBO hiker I met in Caratunk) graciously decided to drive down and bust out these miles with me! In order to achieve this feat, you must hike from the Mason Dixon line in Pennsylvania, through Maryland, West Virginia, ending at the border of Virgina (within 24hours). The clock was ticking, we crossed the Mason Dixon line. A big boulder scramble in the dark woke up my legs real quick. We heard something move, we froze. We could see a mountain lion/bobcat stalking a baby deer. I started making noise and hiking even harder. It didn‚Äôt follow us, thank God. The trail directed us into a meadow. It was still dark out but we could see the stars above us, comforting us and providing a beautiful sparkle as we hiked. The sun finally came up and we boogied through Maryland. We stopped in at Harpers Ferry, West Virginia. Visited the ATC and I got the traditional SOBO polaroid picture and my number. I am southbounder #50 crossing through the halfway point this year! It‚Äôs crazy to think, I started as southbounder #426. We hiked on, trying to make the 24hr window. The sun was setting and a gorgeous cotton candy sky welcomed us into Virginia!!!! 18 hours later, 4 states, and 44 miles ‚ù§Ô∏èWow what a day!! God is good, I thank Him for the strength!

Last summer my brother Bear (10yrs) and I (Fizzy, 8yrs) completed a thru hike of the Appalachian Trail in 99 days.
.
We like to walk, a lot, and our goal when we started in Maine was to hike the 2200 mile trail in the fastest time we could. We were self supported, except for our Dad (Sweeps) who carried the food, and hiked a little slower than us!
.
Understandably @fastestknowntime don‚Äôt keep separate #fkt records for 8 year old girls! And obviously we have a bit more work to do before we catch up with other great thru hikers, @anishhikes @jenpharrdavis @lizthomashiking . Nevertheless we are really proud of what we achieved. Maybe a fastest known kid time??
.
Now, almost a year since we finished the trail at Springer Mountain, we wanted to talk about our experience. So the next few posts will be about the miles we hiked, the pounds we carried, the highs, and the lows of our 2018 SOBO thru hike.
.

Sometimes I look through photos at night when I can‚Äôt sleep. Lyme disease definitely has me fatigued, but going from nonstop activity to virtually no activity has also left me restless.

The last few weeks have been really difficult. With time and space, I‚Äôve realized what made them emotionally draining was not knowing how to move forward. Deciding to hike the trail seemed relatively easy in comparison to some of the decisions we‚Äôve had to make over the past two weeks.

The sunk cost feels so great and the promise of post trail goals felt like they could only be achieved by meeting deadlines. After so many setbacks less than a quarter of the way into the trail, the uncertainty of whether we‚Äôd even finish weighed heavily on my heart and mind.

Instead of seeing the glass half full, I saw it half empty. My Dad told me that, ‚Äúlife is all about adjusting goals to meet reality and accepting it‚Äù. Looking at this picture, I realized we‚Äôve adjusted our goals to meet our reality every single day on the trail, but we weren‚Äôt applying that to the overall goal of completing the trail.

This picture reminds me that the path isn‚Äôt always clear - sometimes you have to down climb, sometimes you have to crawl through a cave, sometimes you have to take your pack off and ask for help - it‚Äôs humbling and challenging, but definitely worthwhile because so much is learned in the process.

I haven‚Äôt received the all clear to go back to the trail yet, but we are going to do a small section over the course of the next week.

I won‚Äôt be pulling big miles, but I will be making progress.

The last two weeks have broken me down in ways I can‚Äôt begin to describe.

I stepped off the trail to recover from a severe concussion and revamp my diet after significant weight loss.

Getting back on trail, I was anxious. I lacked confidence in my body and it‚Äôs capability to tackle mileage.

As someone who firmly believes in mind over matter, I knew something was wrong when I couldn‚Äôt rally Tuesday morning. I couldn‚Äôt push my body anymore and I felt like an absolute failure.

Leaving the trail and coming back to Boston felt final, I couldn‚Äôt bring myself to make the decision. We gave up everything to hike the AT, we had made it through the hardest part, I didn‚Äôt want to give up on this dream, but I couldn‚Äôt keep hiking. Fortunately, @_rolson made it for us.

I was officially diagnosed with Lyme disease this morning.

While I am still physically, mentally and emotionally drained, I know I will be able to rally now that we have an answer and a plan in place.

Couldn‚Äôt be more grateful for the family and friends that have surrounded us and defended the silver lining.

It hasn‚Äôt been easy, but when life gives you Lyme, you make lime aid.

Read more about the last two weeks in my latest blog. Link in profile.

Day 56 | 16.1 miles

With the largest, most technical mountains behind us, we are excited to pick up our mileage.

There are few views in the green tunnel. We haven‚Äôt entered it quite yet, but we are aware that we ate dessert for dinner and experienced some of the most epic views in Maine and New Hampshire.

I don‚Äôt want to lose sight of the beauty in each day. One benefit of trekking through smoother terrain is the ability to look up more often and take in the surrounding forest.

We saw a bear cub and Mama. The cub ran off immediately upon hearing us, but the Mama kept her eyes locked on us, refusing to move until her cub was safe.

We didn‚Äôt get photos of Mama and her cub, but I couldn‚Äôt stop smiling - it‚Äôs pretty amazing to see your favorite animal in its natural habitat.

Day 55 | 6.7 miles

We woke up atop the Smarts Mountain fire tower and took in a gorgeous sunrise. If you ever have a chance to sleep on top of a mountain in a fire tower, I highly recommend it.

We enjoyed a quiet morning before the rain moved in. The descent was a bit more challenging than we expected with several very wet sections of slab. Sometimes the AT is more of a slide than a hike, but we carefully made our way to the road.

We scored an amazing hitch into Lyme, New Hampshire where we enjoyed a burger on the front porch of the general store. We watched the storm for a few hours and were in awe of this quiet and beautiful little New England town.

I had a lovely conversation with the owner of the store, he shared the history of the town and its inhabitants. We resupplied and caught a wonderful hitch back to the trail. She shared that one of Lyme‚Äôs residents rescues bear cubs and releases them into the wild. He also happens to be the star of an amazing film on Panda Bears. Naturally, I geeked out because I am obsessed with Bears.

Overall, it was a pretty awesome day until the mice in the shelter evicted us at 9:30 pm.

Day 54 | 15.1 miles

Some days you rally and Mother Nature rewards you with the most epic sunset.

We came close to stealth camping 4 miles shy of Smarts Mountain. My hip and shoulder were bothering me and I was absolutely exhausted.

Needless to say, I am so glad we pushed it.

As we fell asleep under the stars, I realized it was the 3 year anniversary of my friend‚Äôs passing.

A fellow cancer ninja, she taught me so much about living this one, beautiful life all in. She was fierce and passionate - a truly beautiful soul who taught me about the transformative power of taking risks and adventuring. No doubt she helped me rally.

Thanks for the epic sunset and for giving me the courage to take on this trek, Crush. I am finally filling in the blank you left each of us to define for ourselves in your parting requests:

Third...be vulnerable, take risks, choose adventure. Don‚Äôt let the remnants of melanoma and the fear of a new diagnosis limit you. Create your life, don‚Äôt just show up for it. And most importantly, be kind to yourself - progress over perfection (it will make all of the above a bit easier). üíô

Day 53 | 12.8 miles

400 miles on trail and my last 4,000+ foot peak until Virginia.

The White Mountains ended the way they began with rain, wind and fog. It was as if Mother Nature wanted to remind us how far we‚Äôd come and all the beauty that we experienced in between as we trekked through the most challenging and stunning section of the AT.

Day 52 | 9 miles

After a stormy night, we woke up to a beautiful day. We got an early start, knowing full well our day would end with a relatively tough climb halfway up Mt Moosilauke.

The mileage was fairly easy, but knowing we had to finish on a tough section filled me with dread.

As we approached the final section, the signs warned us to turn back if we didn‚Äôt think we were physically capable. Nothing like a good warning to really amp up the anxiety level.

Turns out, it was a fairly long stair stepping route with a few bolts and slab climbing sections equipped with metal bars and some stairs. There were some dicey segments, but I was glad to be climbing up rather than descending.

The section was challenging but rewarding as we climbed up along a gorgeous set of falls.

Day 51 | 9.8 miles

We took our 50th day on trail off @notchhostel - which was absolutely amazing. We explored Lincoln, NH and enjoyed time at One Love Brewery among other staples.

We got back on trail the next day. I was nervous about the Kinsman‚Äôs, especially with the weather, but we took it slow.

With the fog, we saw very little at the summit, but it made the day beautiful in a different way as we looked at nature from another perspective.

We hiked down along waterfalls, which was a pleasant surprise. I was so focused on how many peaks we were taking on and what the terrain was like, I forgot to look at the other landmarks on the map.

The Kinsman‚Äôs were challenging, but I didn‚Äôt find them as difficult as they were rumored to be. Sometimes the forewarnings from other hikers build up so much anticipation, it makes me doubt my abilities.

I‚Äôm glad we pushed it and I didn‚Äôt let the weather and idea of wet rock scramble descent deter me.

Day 48 | 12.7 miles

A pretty beautiful 4 summit day trekking over Zealand Mountain, Mt Guyout, South Twin Mountain and Galehead Mountain.

We ended the day ‚Äúhiking‚Äù halfway up Garfield. The hike was more of a hand over hand vertical ascent up a small stream/waterfall.

It was an incredibly challenging way to end the day, I was totally spent. Rather than push it up the final pitch, I turned around and sat down.

I caught the golden hour, looking out over all that we had hiked. The moment was made more peaceful by the water running down the rocks and the fact that I was the only soul on that section of trail. It was pretty special to sit and reflect as our time in the whites is coming to an end.

I finished the last section and met up with the rest of our crew where we enjoyed laughs and dinner after a long, but epic day on trail.

While we didn‚Äôt grow up together, seeing this girl made me realize how much I miss ‚Äúhome‚Äù. Missing all the incredible people in my life a little extra today and so grateful for this one! Day 45 | 7.1 miles

Third time is a charm. The day started like the last two with aggressive wind, fog and rain. Unlike the last two days, the forecast had promise - trending clear.

The morning weather was unsafe. Even with the proper gear, hypothermia was a major risk, forcing us to wait it out and hope for enough daylight and visibility to make it over Mt Washington.

We set out around noon. The wind and fog continued as we trekked around Adams, Jefferson and Clay. There were moments when the fog cleared, revealing the traverse, showing us how far we‚Äôd come.

As we made the ascent up Mt Washington, I was filled with so much joy (despite the 70 mph gusts of wind). 24 hours earlier, I was questioning my ability to finish this thru hike, and now I was about to summit the mountain that made me feel incapable.

As we hiked down with the sun, I was filled with gratitude for this wild adventure and all of its ups and downs.

Day 43 | 3 miles
Day 44 | 0 miles

We woke up at 4 am, ready to take on the Presidential Traverse. We knew weather would be moving in, so we needed to move quickly.

Unfortunately, the weather combined with my previous ascent of Mt Washington (different route), psyched me out.

We came over Mt Madison in 50 mph winds and fog. I doubted my ability to get over Washington, already knowing the traverse was out of the question for me.

We opted to stay at Madison Spring Hut, knowing the weather would only deteriorate further.

The next day we woke up and hit the trail by 6 am. We made it a little over 1.5 miles in low visibility before we were pelted with freezing rain and aggressive winds. Crushed, we turned back.

Turning back is hard, it‚Äôs made even more difficult by the limited options for shelter and the inability to tent above tree line. I know it‚Äôs the right decision, but it doesn‚Äôt make it any easier and I often question my abilities as a result. It‚Äôs days like these that can zap your confidence and make the challenges ahead feel insurmountable.

300 miles on trail!

After a zero at Rattle River, we opted to go NOBO over the Wildcats. We lightened our packs down to the essentials and got dropped off at Pinkham Notch.

I can see why people recommend going NOBO over this range. The SOBO descent, while not impossible, is both a mental and physical game. It is incredibly long. Personally, I‚Äôd rather climb technical sections rather than descend them.

We reached the top and saw the gondola, it‚Äôs definitely different to summit a mountain and see so much civilization after our time in Maine.

Day 34 | 0 miles
Day 35 | 5.5 miles
Day 36 | 7.1 miles

We took a zero at Rattle River after evacuating our friend from Mahoosuc Arm.

We debated going back in, but I knew the only way forward was to go back to where we left off.

On day 35, we took a side trail to the top of Mahoosuc Arm. I was a mess, crying and shaking with fear as we approached the top. We made it down the arm and stealth camped ahead of the notch.

Day 36 we hit Mahoosuc Notch and I was paralyzed with fear looking at boulders twice my size wondering how I‚Äôd get over, under or around them. I also couldn‚Äôt help but think about what would happen if one of us got injured and how long it would take for us to be rescued. It seems silly, but that‚Äôs where my head was after our experience on the arm.

With @_rolson coaching me, I made it through the mile of bouldering that makes up Mahoosuc Notch and we camped with some friends at Carlo Col.

Going back in was one of the most mentally and physically draining experiences, but I‚Äôm glad that I did it. Sometimes we need to face the things that scare us the most to move forward. I‚Äôm not 100% confident in my footing yet, but I know it will get better with each step.

Day 33 | 6 miles

We woke up before the sun. After a rough day yesterday, we wanted to give ourselves as much time as possible to get down Mahoosuc Arm and through Mahoosuc Notch.

We saw beavers playing in the pond and caught a beautiful sunrise at the top of the arm.

The picture perfect morning took an unexpected turn, when our friend fell and seriously injured her leg. We quickly realized she wouldn‚Äôt be able to walk out and were fortunate to have some kind souls help us get her safely down to Speck Pond Lean-to by land and water.

Despite the circumstances, the trek down was surprisingly filled with laughter. That‚Äôs how you know you‚Äôre in good company, when one of the most challenging situations is made lighter and brighter.

When we reached the shelter it became clear, she would need to be airlifted out.

People say this trail gives and takes, and I believe that is true. While we‚Äôd never wish for this to happen, we were grateful for the community that surrounded and supported us.

The truth is, it can happen to any hiker, it doesn‚Äôt matter how many miles you‚Äôve hiked, how much you gave up to thru-hike or how long you‚Äôve dreamt or planned your hike.

Thank you to the people who stopped their hike and helped us. Our friend is on the mend, but we will certainly miss having her on trail with us as we continue our trek to Georgia in the coming days.

We won‚Äôt take a moment of this thru-hike for granted moving forward.

Day 31 | 4.5 miles

A full month on trail. We officially have trail names, we‚Äôve hiked 261.4 miles and we are so close to the Maine/New Hampshire border.

We planned on 8-11 miles today, but Mother Nature had something else in mind to celebrate our first month on trail - a thunder storm, reminiscent of our first several nights out here.

Fortunately, we could see the storm moving in and were able to get curled up below tree line. We waited out the worst of the storm and then made the decision to backtrack almost 2 miles to the last shelter.

It was pretty disappointing, but the right choice given the conditions.

Day 28 | 12.5 miles

Another day, another mountain range. The AT is becoming a routine, which in some ways is wonderful, but in other ways means I‚Äôm losing touch with the beauty that surrounds me.

Today, I breezed past an old AT sign from the original trail. @_rolson called it out and I backtracked to see it.

I‚Äôve seen replicas and cleaned up versions at hostels, but to see one of the originals on a tree despite the trail being re-routed over the years was pretty special.

This trail has a rich history and I love learning about it. I also feel incredibly grateful for those that created it, maintain it and have walked it before me. There is a lot of wisdom in this mountain range. Crazy to think, I‚Äôm still at the beginning.

Day 27 | 11.9 miles ‚ÄúThe human spirit needs places where nature has not been rearranged by the hand of man.‚Äù - unknown

Today was pretty beautiful for a number of reasons. This section of trail reminds me of northern Maine with so many puds & suds (pointless and stupid ups and downs). At times, it can be aggravating, but more and more I‚Äôm finding myself lost in my own thoughts, flowing with the trail.

We emerged at an overlook where folks were painting the lakes and ridges beyond and I was struck by this quote.

Trekking through Maine has been such a transformative experience thus far. It‚Äôs hard to believe we‚Äôve only been out here for 26 days. In some ways (quite possibly the best ways), it feels like a lifetime.

The day was made even brighter by some incredible trail magic. A couple served us hot dogs, chips and soda right by our stealth site. They shared stories of the people they‚Äôve met and experiences they‚Äôve had. We laughed a lot and I‚Äôve come to the conclusion that the AT community is filled with incredible storytellers.

Day 26 | 4 miles

We hiked into Rangely, which is halfway between the equator and North Pole. We enjoyed a PBR for second breakfast at Hiker Hut and got shuttled into town. It was a pretty amazing morning and afternoon filled with good food, lots of laughs and a decent amount of productivity at the library.

We lucked out with the best hitch, a couple took us to resupply at IGA and dropped us off at the trail head. They were so kind and had the sweetest pup.

Getting back on trail was rough, but we successfully did our first ‚Äútrek through town day‚Äù and resisted the urge to stop and stay the night (which let‚Äôs be honest, a shower, warm bed and being able to ship gear home would have been pretty awesome). Instead, I just got a picture with this sign.

Day 23 | 8.4 miles

Back on the trail after an amazing stay at Hostel of Maine aka HoME. It was hard to leave, especially given the heat.

Town days are not only busy with resupply, logistics planning, and catching up on personal life to dos, they are also a chance to reconnect with the world off trail. Town days are pure magic, but I‚Äôm often ready to get back on trail.

Leaving HoME was surprisingly hard. Town can be an escape from the sometimes isolating trail. On trail, you have hours on end to think and process, which can be challenging when paired with the obstacles Mother Nature has created for us to traverse.

This crew is breaking up as we head out, 3 of us are continuing on while 2 are stepping away from the trail. It‚Äôs hard when friends leave the trail, each person brings such a unique dynamic and perspective to trail life. It‚Äôs what makes the AT community so beautiful.

As we hiked away from Stratton, we saw the ranges we‚Äôve recently hiked. I still find it interesting that looking back helps to propel me forward.

Day 21 | 9.4 miles

We‚Äôve come a long way and while the days don‚Äôt always go as planned, sometimes the best summits come after a challenging day.

Day 20 | 5.2 miles

Today was a bit rough, as we ascended Little Bigelow we saw Avery go into a complete cloud. The wind and rain picked up and I was pretty nervous to summit the remaining Bigelows given the conditions. Our friends were hiking ahead to Stratton, so it was a very tough (read: emotional) call. I‚Äôm also type A and struggle when I don‚Äôt meet my intended mileage.

Ultimately, we decided to near-o and set up camp. I wanted to be resilient and push through, but I also knew I wouldn‚Äôt enjoy the summits as much and the descents would be tricky given the tread is beginning to wear down on my trail runners.

Tomorrow is a new day and the forecast is looking bright.

I‚Äôve been asked frequently, why the AT? Why now?

I‚Äôve been journaling daily on the trail and finally found some words to scratch the surface of why I‚Äôm hiking the AT.

As I summited Avery Peak and looked out over Sugarloaf it became clear that my love for mountains started at an early age.

My mountain roots were born on Sugarloaf where I learned to ski, nourished in the White Mountains of New Hampshire where I hiked and camped and rediscovered in Shenandoah after my melanoma diagnosis.

Starting in Maine has been incredibly challenging, I feel like there are more tears than laughter at times. For me, it‚Äôs hard not to let fear take over, but with the support of @_rolson and our trail family, we are finding our way and are over 220 miles in.

Click the link in my profile to read my first blog.

Day 16 | 9 miles

We woke up early to take on the 9 mile hike to Pleasant Pond. We‚Äôve been gaining trail legs and adjusting to life on the trail, so we haven‚Äôt really had the energy or time to enjoy Maine‚Äôs hidden gems, particularly the stunning and often remote swimming holes.

Today, we were determined to change that. We walked down a small side trail and emerged on a dock. We swam, then sat on the floating dock for awhile to dry off and take it all in.

I‚Äôm finding, in the effort to log miles, it‚Äôs easy to miss the beauty of these experiences. Hoping I can find a balance as we continue our trek.

Day 11 | 15.1 miles

No doubt, one of the best days on trail so far - by 6 am, I hit the 100 mile mark on my AT SOBO trek and by 5:30 pm I emerged from the 100 mile wilderness.

Still at a loss for words as I look back on the ridges and valleys of our trek so far. It‚Äôs hard to believe it‚Äôs just the beginning.

I‚Äôm excited to see what the rest of the trail has in store, but first a zero or two at Shaw‚Äôs Hiker Hostel.

Day 10 | 10.9 miles

Nearing the end of the 100 mile wilderness, we finished our last significant mountain range and my hiker hunger is beginning to kick in (or maybe I‚Äôm just really ready for town and food). It may be the light at the end of this 100 mile wilderness, but I‚Äôm beginning to enjoy the days more. The wilderness has become more manageable or maybe I stopped fighting it and learned to accept and embrace it for what it is.

Day 9 | 9.9 Miles

Started the day off strong, crushing mileage and optimistic we‚Äôd be able to make a little over 16 miles.

The wilderness had something else in mind, the Chairbacks were pretty challenging and technical. We got caught in an intense storm and sat below the ledge of the Chairbacks waiting it out.

We summited when there was a gap in the storm and had some pretty amazing views despite the clouds.

I could see below where we hunkered down for the storm, and for the first time I could see the range of mountains we‚Äôve covered in the wilderness.
When you‚Äôre winding through the 100 mile wilderness, it‚Äôs hard to understand or see the big picture. It finally came together for me on that summit and it was breathtaking.

I cannot say enough good things about Shaw's! @shawshikerhostel ! They are extremely knowledgeable and know these woods better than anyone else. I was 15 miles from finishing the 100 mile wilderness when my sandals couldn't go any further, they hiked up in the deep woods to meet me carying several new pairs of shoes for me to try on! What happened experience that was! I was worried that because everyone knows Shaw's and it's the trendy place to stay that it might be noisy but it wasn't, I slept so good!!

6.29- Bald Mountain Brook Lean-to- mi 136.5

Hiked a short 9 mile day today, and summited Moxie Bald Mountain. We sat up at this chilly summit for lunch and watched the clouds roll over the still landscape around us. On the trail down, I found some lady slippers among the pines and took a sketch break. I love how well my Strathmore travel pad is holding up! Hiking into Caratunk tomorrow!

6.25- Leeman Brook Lean-To- mi 111.5-

This is a collection of photos from the last couple of days: Pines at the last campsite, a view of a mirror lake from Barren Ledges,  a clear day's summit of White Cap Mountain (with dog). And the 100 mile marker at last, which I crossed this morning. It's been 8 days in the 100MW, and it feels so good to be out here. It's hard to imagine the next stage! Lots of feelings. 6.21- Logan Brook campsite- mi 71.4

Today was a 12 mi day, and everything is soaked. The rain last night has saturated all the colors in this forest, and it's impossible not to stare at trees and plants too long. I heard loons today from a nearby lake! Entrancing, unearthly sound. Maine is incredible. And also 90% water.

This was my second and final shakedown hike before I start my SOBO thruhike in Maine on July 3rd. This 40 miles (from Neals Gap to Dicks Creek) took me twice as long as the first 40 miles from Amicalola to Neals Gap which I did in two days. I spent this 4 days in non stop rain. I felt like Forrest Gump, there was little bitty stingin' rain, and big ol' fat rain, rain that flew in sideways... morale was low one the fourth day (the picture of me carrying my once favorite shoes). I will be switching to hiking sandles, maybe @chacofootwear . I also am going to try out an ultralight hammock, maybe the @hummingbirdhammocks and the Herron tarp. The bivy was just too messy in this kind of rain and the tarps did not provide enough coverage, even when I doubled it to try and square out that wierd hexagon shape.

Backpacking has been really good to me over the years. I feel free, independent, strong, happy, connected, simple, and just right when I‚Äôm in the woods. It‚Äôs scary and tiring and boring and really hard sometimes. The people you meet on the trail are immediately your new best friends who help you and are there for you and you will do anything to help them too. You eat for fuel. You smell and you are caked in layers of dirt. Your body aches from head to toe but a night‚Äôs rest will usually do the trick (usually). The best part is that when you are out there, you gain perspective. You have time to think.  Your interactions and thoughts are deep.  You are not connected to your phone, not stressed out at work. You breathe fresh mountain air with every breath, and you drink water from cold streams.  You don‚Äôt want to go home. I am beyond excited to spend 6 months this year hiking the Appalachian Trail with the person who I trust, love, and look up to most. He will be hiking it on his 10 year anniversary of thru-hiking it north-bound when he had just finished college. We will start in Maine in late June and walk home (and then some!), perhaps in time for Thanksgiving with family.
